"# Chapter 9 — Trace and watch: introspection over time

Snapshot introspection tells you what a value is right now. Sometimes you need the temporal dimension — what has this verb been called with, over the last hundred calls? What has this expression evaluated to over the last twenty prompts? For that Motoi has `,trace` and `,watch`, and both produce logs you can query as data.

## 9.1 Why over time?

A single snapshot answers *what is this?*. A log answers *how did this become what it is?*. For pure code the two are equivalent — the value tells the whole story. For code with state, or for programs that evolve across many calls, the log is where the answers live.

## 9.2 ,trace — record every call to a verb

`,trace foo` at the REPL wraps the verb `foo` in a tracing shim. Every subsequent call is recorded with its arguments and return value.

```
> ,trace my-verb
tracing my-verb

> (my-verb 42)
=> \"result\"
> (my-verb 100)
=> \"result-2\"

> ,trace-log my-verb
call 1: (my-verb 42) => \"result\"
call 2: (my-verb 100) => \"result-2\"
```

The trace log is a value. You can dump it with `,trace-log`, filter it, aggregate it, feed it to the LLM for pattern-finding.

The trace shim is per-verb. Multiple verbs can be traced at once; each has its own log.

## 9.3 ,untrace — stop recording

`,untrace foo` removes the shim. Subsequent calls are not recorded. The log accumulated so far is preserved until you clear it explicitly.

```
> ,untrace my-verb
untraced my-verb (12 calls recorded)

> ,trace-log my-verb
12 calls in log
```

You can inspect the log after untracing. The shim is gone but the data persists.

## 9.4 ,watch — re-evaluate on every prompt

`,watch expr` adds an expression to the watch list. Every time you hit enter at the REPL, every watched expression is re-evaluated and its current value is displayed.

```
> ,watch (length my-list)
watching: (length my-list) = 3

> (set! my-list (cons 99 my-list))
=> ()
(length my-list) = 4

> (set! my-list (cons 98 my-list))
=> ()
(length my-list) = 5
```

The watch line refreshes on every prompt. You see how the value evolves as you make changes.

Watch is useful for state debugging. Set up watches on the pieces of state you care about, then mutate. Every mutation shows you the new state without you having to re-type the query.

