## 9.17 A worked example

You are debugging a game. The player's score is jumping around unpredictably. You do not know which code is changing it.

```
> ,trace update-score
tracing update-score

> (play-game)
... game runs ...

> ,trace-log update-score
call 1: (update-score 10) => 10
call 2: (update-score 20) => 30
call 3: (update-score -100) => -70
call 4: (update-score 5) => -65
```

Call 3 subtracted 100. That is the mystery. Now you go read the code that decides to call `update-score` with -100 and find the bug.

Two commands (,trace and ,trace-log) and you have identified the culprit call.

