## 9.20 A closing observation

Time is the dimension most languages leave out of their introspection story. Motoi keeps it in. Traces and watches turn evaluation into a queryable log, and once you have the log everything about program history becomes debuggable in the same way values are debuggable.

If you have never worked with a language that lets you turn on tracing without a debugger, this will feel like a small miracle. Two commands. Every call recorded. Every call queryable. That is the whole tool.

## 9.21 Chapter closes with an invitation

Try `,trace` on the next verb you find yourself wondering about. Any verb. `,trace map`. `,trace cortex/write`. `,trace your-cart-main`. Then use the verb. Then `,trace-log <name>`. See what you get.

The trace log will surprise you. You will see calls you did not remember making. You will see arguments you did not remember passing. That surprise is a signal — the log is showing you what actually happened, not what you thought was happening.

Turn the page. Chapter 10 opens Cortex.

## 9.22 Deep-seed — trace log shape

Each trace log entry is a record:

```scheme
(:call-num integer
 :timestamp seconds
 :args list
 :return value
 :duration-ms number
 :caller symbol-or-nil
 :fuel-used integer)
```

Seven fields. You can filter or sort by any of them. Common queries:

```scheme
;; slowest calls
(sort-by :duration-ms > (trace-log 'my-verb))

;; calls in the last 10 seconds
(filter
  (lambda (e) (< (- (current-second) (assoc :timestamp e)) 10))
  (trace-log 'my-verb))

;; total fuel used by this verb
(apply + (map (lambda (e) (assoc :fuel-used e)) (trace-log 'my-verb)))
```

The trace log is data. Every query is a filter or a projection. The primitives compose.

## 9.23 Deep-seed — watch as a poor programmer's dashboard

If you set up several watches on related state, you get a small live dashboard at the REPL:

```
> ,watch (length players)
> ,watch (map :score players)
> ,watch (game-state)

watching: (length players) = 4
watching: (map :score players) = (100 85 42 0)
watching: (game-state) = 'in-progress
```

Every prompt refreshes all three lines. You have a live view of your game state without opening a UI.

This is watch's real payoff — a poor programmer's dashboard, built from Scheme primitives, updating on every command.

Turn the page.

