## 9.25 Deep-seed — sampling

For high-frequency verbs, full tracing can be expensive. Motoi's trace shim supports sampling — record one call in every N.

```
> ,trace paint-dot :sample-rate 100
tracing paint-dot (1 in 100)

> (draw-scene)
... paint-dot called 30000 times ...

> ,trace-log paint-dot
300 calls in log (sampled 1/100)
```

The log has 300 entries instead of 30000. You get statistical coverage without the memory cost of a full trace.

Sampling is what makes tracing viable for verbs called in tight loops. Without it, tracing a graphics-inner-loop verb would explode memory. With it, you get enough data to spot patterns and outliers.

## 9.26 Deep-seed — trace and LLM

Chapter 13 will introduce `tell-story` and `reflect`. Both consume trace logs and produce narrative.

```scheme
(tell-story (trace-log 'my-verb))
;; => \"You called my-verb 12 times. The first three used small inputs; then a big jump to 100.
;;     The fourth call returned an unusual negative — that's where the bug is.\"
```

The LLM reads the log, spots patterns, tells you what happened in prose. Grounded in the actual data. No confabulation — the log is right there.

## 9.27 Deep-seed — traces as Cortex records

You can persist a trace to Cortex for durable analysis:

```scheme
(for-each
  (lambda (entry)
    (cortex/record
      :subject 'my-verb
      :predicate 'called
      :object entry
      :at (assoc :timestamp entry)
      :source 'trace-log))
  (trace-log 'my-verb))
```

Now the trace lives across sessions. Next week you can query Cortex for every call to `my-verb` and see how usage evolved. This is what having introspection as data enables — traces are just values you can persist, filter, and query alongside everything else.

Turn the page. Chapter 10 opens Cortex directly.

## 9.28 A final note

Trace and watch are Motoi's temporal introspection primitives. They are small (two REPL commands plus a handful of verbs) but they open up a whole dimension of the introspection story.

Static introspection tells you what things are. Temporal introspection tells you how they got there. Together they cover most debugging.

The Wave 3 authoring pass will extend this seed into a full chapter with worked case studies of real bugs found via trace, dashboards built with watch, and integration patterns with Cortex.

Turn the page. Chapter 10 awaits.

## 9.29 Deep-seed — the trace shim mechanics

The trace shim works by replacing the verb binding with a wrapping procedure. The original verb is preserved on the shim, and every call goes through the wrapper first.

Roughly:

```scheme
(define (make-trace-shim original-verb log-name)
  (lambda args
    (let ((t0 (current-second))
          (call-num (next-call-number log-name)))
      (let ((result (apply original-verb args)))
        (record-trace-entry log-name call-num t0 args result)
        result))))
```

The shim measures time, counts the call, applies the original, records the entry, returns the result. The caller does not notice the wrapping.

`,untrace` restores the original binding by removing the shim. The log records survive.

This is a small piece of machinery but it is what makes tracing composable. Any verb can be traced. Untracing is instant. Multiple verbs can be traced simultaneously.

## 9.30 Deep-seed — a working debugging scenario

Say you have a cart that computes a score based on many small inputs. The output is wrong but you cannot find where.

**Step 1.** Trace the top-level scoring verb.

```
> ,trace compute-final-score
```

**Step 2.** Trace the inner computation.

```
> ,trace compute-partial-score
```

**Step 3.** Run the cart once.

```
> (run-my-cart)
```

**Step 4.** Introspect both logs.

```
> ,trace-log compute-final-score
> ,trace-log compute-partial-score
```

**Step 5.** Correlate. The partial-score calls that fed into the final-score should sum to the final score. If they do not, either the sum is wrong or a call is missing. If they do, the bug is upstream of partial-score.

Two trace commands. Two logs. Systematic debugging without a debugger.

Turn the page. Chapter 10 opens Cortex.

## 9.31 A last observation

Trace is one of those tools that changes how you think about debugging once you have it. You stop trying to reason about what code did and start looking at what code did. The log is authoritative. The reasoning is derivative.

That shift is worth a lot. Reasoning is expensive and error-prone; reading a log is cheap and honest.

If Motoi did nothing else right, having trace as a two-command REPL primitive would still make it a nice language to debug in. Combined with everything else in this book, it becomes a genuinely powerful debugging surface.

Turn the page. Chapter 10 opens Cortex — the persistent memory graph where facts live across sessions and every record carries provenance, source, and time as first-class fields you can query and filter to trace the history of any piece of the program state that the program chose to remember across runs and use as substrate for adaptive behavior later on in the session or the next one.
